{"questionId":"9069515","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The overall equation for the production of hydrogen cyanide, HCN, is shown below.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">CH<sub>4</sub> (g) + NH<sub>3</sub> (g) +<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>O<sub>2</sub> (g) → HCN (g) + 3H<sub>2</sub>O (g)</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>State why NH<sub>3</sub> is a Lewis base.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>donates «lone/non-bonding» pair of electrons ✔</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9069515","referenceCode":"22M.2.hl.TZ2.a(i)","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"State why NH3 is a Lewis base.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"a(i)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 18: Acids and bases","18.1 Lewis acids and bases","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 18: Acids and bases"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}